rocplot = function(pred, truth){
  predob = prediction(pred, truth)
  perf = performance(predob, "tpr", "fpr")
  plot(perf)
}

# train&test
set.seed(666)
n_train = sample.int(n = nrow(newdata), size = floor(.70*nrow(newdata)), replace = F)
n_test = -n_train
train = newdata[n_train,]
test = newdata[n_test,]
n = dim(test)[1]
# logistic regression
m_lr1 = glm(Loan_Status~., data = train, family = binomial)

## scale features to fall on the closed [0,1] interval
Loan_sta[Loan_sta == 'Y'] <- 1
Loan_sta[Loan_sta == 'N'] <- 0
Loan_sta <- as.numeric(Loan_sta)
nnewdata <- data.frame(completeData, Loan_sta)
scale01 <- function(x) {
    (x - min(x))/(max(x) - min(x))
}
nnewdata['Dependents'] <- scale01(nnewdata['Dependents'])
nnewdata['ApplicantIncome'] <- scale01(nnewdata['ApplicantIncome'])
nnewdata['CoapplicantIncome'] <- scale01(nnewdata['CoapplicantIncome'])
nnewdata['LoanAmount'] <- scale01(nnewdata['LoanAmount'])
nnewdata['Loan_Amount_Term'] <- scale01(nnewdata['Loan_Amount_Term'])
nnewdata['Property_Area'] <- scale01(nnewdata['Property_Area'])

Setting the linear.output to FALSE and the err.fct to “ce” indicates that we are performing a classification, and forces the model to output what we may interpret as a probability of each observation belonging to Survival class 1.

set.seed(666)

loan_NN1 <- neuralnet(Loan_sta ~ Gender+Married+Dependents+Education+Self_Employed+ApplicantIncome+
                        CoapplicantIncome+LoanAmount+Loan_Amount_Term+Property_Area, train2, 
                      linear.output = FALSE, err.fct = "ce", likelihood = TRUE)

plot(loan_NN1, rep = "best")

The black lines show the connections between each layer and the weights on each connection while the blue lines show the bias term added in each step. The bias can be thought as the intercept of a linear model.

The error displayed in this plot is the cross-entropy error, which is a measure of the differences between the predicted and observed output for each of the observations in the Loan data set.

Problems that occur during neural network training is overfitting. The error on the training set is driven to a very small value, but when new data is presented to the network the error is large. The network has memorized the training examples, but it has not learned to generalize to new situations. One method for improving network generalization is to use a network that is just large enough to provide an adequate fit. Another one is using dropout.
